    <section id="alzheimers-and-the-leaky-brain" class="reveal">
      <h2>Alzheimer's and the Leaky Brain</h2>

      <p>The relationship between blood-brain barrier dysfunction and Alzheimer's disease is now one of the most active areas of dementia research — and one of the most consequential revisions to the prevailing theory of the disease.</p>

      <p>The amyloid hypothesis, which has dominated Alzheimer's research for three decades, holds that the accumulation of amyloid-beta plaques triggers a cascade leading to neurodegeneration. Recent clinical trial failures of amyloid-targeting drugs — despite successfully clearing plaques in some patients — have forced the field to seriously consider whether plaque accumulation is a cause or a symptom.</p>

      <p>The blood-brain barrier story suggests a more complex picture. Amyloid-beta is produced as a normal byproduct of neuronal activity and is continuously cleared from brain tissue through the glymphatic system and through active transport across the blood-brain barrier. When the barrier's transport systems fail — as they do with age and inflammation — amyloid clearance is impaired, and plaques accumulate. In this model, barrier dysfunction is upstream of amyloid accumulation, not downstream of it.</p>

      <p>APOE4, the strongest genetic risk factor for Alzheimer's, expresses at high levels in pericytes — the barrier's vascular support cells — and appears to cause pericyte dysfunction that directly increases permeability. This provides a plausible mechanism for the APOE4 risk that doesn't run through amyloid at all, or at least not as the primary step.</p>

      <p>The emerging therapeutic hypothesis is that protecting and restoring barrier integrity — through anti-inflammatory interventions, sleep optimization, and potentially targeted pharmacology — may reduce Alzheimer's risk by improving amyloid clearance and reducing the neuroinflammation that the barrier normally prevents.</p>
    </section>

