    <section id="long-covid-and-barrier-disruption" class="reveal">
      <h2>Long COVID and Barrier Disruption</h2>

      <p>The blood-brain barrier became significantly more prominent in public discourse in 2022-2024 as researchers began mapping the mechanisms of long COVID's neurological symptoms: brain fog, cognitive impairment, fatigue, and mood disruption that persist months or years after acute infection.</p>

      <p>SARS-CoV-2 has been shown to infect pericytes and endothelial cells in the cerebral vasculature, directly damaging the structural elements of the barrier. The virus also drives systemic inflammation that further degrades tight junction proteins. And viral particles or inflammatory mediators entering through a compromised barrier activate microglia, generating neuroinflammation that persists after the virus has cleared peripheral tissues.</p>

      <p>Cerebrospinal fluid studies in long COVID patients have found elevated cytokines, chemokines, and markers of neuroinflammation — evidence of an ongoing immune response inside the brain in people who otherwise appear to have recovered. The blood-brain barrier appears to be the point of entry.</p>

      <p>This is not an argument about COVID specifically — the issue of post-viral syndromes triggering sustained neuroinflammation through barrier disruption likely applies to other pathogens too. It is, however, a concrete illustration of what happens at a cellular level when the barrier fails to do its job.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="exercise-the-unexpected-protector" class="reveal">
      <h2>Exercise: The Unexpected Protector</h2>

      <p>In February 2026, a study published in <em>Nature</em> identified a specific mechanism by which exercise protects the blood-brain barrier in aging.</p>

      <p>Physical activity, the researchers found, stimulates the liver to produce an enzyme called GPLD1. GPLD1 is released into the bloodstream and acts on the cerebral vasculature to remove a protein called heparan sulfate proteoglycan that accumulates with age and disrupts tight junction function. In aging mouse models, exercise-stimulated GPLD1 production restored barrier integrity to near-youthful levels.</p>

      <p>This provides a molecular mechanism for the long-observed association between physical activity and reduced risk of cognitive decline. The brain benefits from exercise not only through BDNF, reduced vascular disease risk, and improved metabolic regulation — but through a liver-mediated signal that directly repairs the barrier protecting it.</p>
    </section>

