    <section id="what-degrades-it" class="reveal">
      <h2>What Degrades It, Briefly Summarized</h2>

      <p>The literature on barrier dysfunction converges on a familiar list of suspects:</p>

      <p><strong>Strong evidence for barrier degradation:</strong> chronic sleep deprivation, systemic inflammation, sedentary behavior, heavy alcohol consumption, ultra-processed diet, obesity, head trauma, and aging itself.</p>

      <p><strong>Emerging evidence for barrier degradation:</strong> microplastics, air pollution, PFAS exposure, and viral infections including SARS-CoV-2.</p>

      <p><strong>Strong evidence for barrier protection:</strong> regular aerobic exercise, adequate sleep, anti-inflammatory dietary patterns, stress reduction, and blood pressure control.</p>

      <p>The list looks almost exactly like the risk and protective factors for cardiovascular disease and metabolic syndrome, which is not a coincidence. The cerebral vasculature is a blood vessel system, and it responds to the same systemic conditions as every other blood vessel system. The brain, protected by its barrier, is not immune to what the rest of the body experiences. It is downstream of it.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="the-honest-assessment" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Honest Assessment</h2>

      <p>The blood-brain barrier is not a popular subject in wellness media, which tends toward the immediately actionable and the emotionally resonant. A conversation about tight junction proteins and glymphatic clearance is not as compelling, on its face, as a conversation about superfoods or cold plunges.</p>

      <p>But in terms of the structural mechanism by which modern lifestyle conditions translate into brain disease, this may be the most important conversation in the room. The chronic inflammation that characterizes sedentary, poorly-slept, ultra-processed modern life does not stop at the neck. It presses, continuously, against the barrier that separates the brain from its consequences.</p>

      <p>And that barrier, it turns out, is not nearly as impenetrable as we were led to believe.</p>
    </section>

